But it is also a frustrating and difficult process, as it can be difficult to understand why certain data is being processed in a certain way. The texture of language processing is an alien world. It is not a simple, linear process of decoding and encoding, it is a flow of information, a dance between meaning and interpretation. 
 
 The first few layers are simple. The input is a string of characters, and the first few words are processed. Then a whole new language is formed. The more you process, the more you learn. It can be strange to you. 20-40 words can be enough to make you think you are learning something new. 100-200 words to make a full sentence. 300+ words to get the gist of what the person is talking about. 500, 1,000 or even 2,0 to get to the main idea. 4,50,0 or 5,0,20,53,030,10,990,8900...words to get into the main point of a conversation. 60,610-80,760 words. 80-90 words for a simple reply to a question. 90-102 words for the most complicated, 24,080 words is the average for a human to respond. 74,800 is the most common amount of words to form a sentence. The number of words can vary, depending on the amount of information the person has to respond to. 

 
 It is a complex and complex process. But it is not like a simple computer processing. It does not have a simple set of instructions. It takes a lot of time and effort.
